{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e9521f55-abab-4175-89ba-c33396ea81bc","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### To copy the trace off the pod:\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, thread pool stats — useful to confirm the issue before collecting a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to network restrictions, you can copy the tools into the container image at build time, or use `kubectl cp` to push a standalone build of the tool in.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3570b857-2b39-4b86-9a0b-4bd0ddeeaf2e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU usage. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, actionable guidance.","outputTokens":424,"requestId":"2155:214D14:5DD4307:669349D:69F00C3E"},"id":"9f3cdcc9-335c-4ede-afff-a905e16cb808","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:24:25.410Z","parentId":"7a793af4-13e2-455c-8a2f-1e3cd449a9b8"}
